Both define object shapes, but differ in key ways:

interface User {
  name: string;
}
interface User { age: number; } // declaration merging!

type User = {
  name: string;
};
// type User = { age: number }; // ERROR: duplicate

Key differences:
• interface: declaration merging, extends, better error messages
• type: unions, intersections, mapped types, tuples, primitives

type Status = 'active' | 'inactive'; // only type can do this
type Pair = [string, number]; // only type can do this

Guideline: Use interface for objects, type for everything else.

Built-in types that transform other types:

interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

Partial<User> — all properties optional
{ id?: number; name?: string; email?: string; }

Required<User> — all properties required

Pick<User, 'id' | 'name'> — only selected properties
{ id: number; name: string; }

Omit<User, 'email'> — everything except specified
{ id: number; name: string; }

Common in React:
type Props = Pick<User, 'name' | 'email'>;
type UpdatePayload = Partial<Omit<User, 'id'>>;

Narrowing refines a type within a conditional block:

function process(value: string | number) {
  if (typeof value === 'string') {
    value.toUpperCase(); // TS knows it's string here
  } else {
    value.toFixed(2); // TS knows it's number here
  }
}

Narrowing techniques:
• typeof — primitives
• instanceof — classes
• 'property' in obj — object shapes
• Discriminated unions — type field
• Type predicates — custom: function isUser(x): x is User
• Truthiness — if (value) { ... }

Discriminated unions are the most powerful pattern for complex narrowing.

A union type where each member has a shared literal property (discriminant) that TypeScript can use for narrowing:

type Result =
  | { status: 'success'; data: User }
  | { status: 'error'; message: string }
  | { status: 'loading' };

function handle(result: Result) {
  switch (result.status) {
    case 'success':
      result.data; // TS knows data exists
      break;
    case 'error':
      result.message; // TS knows message exists
      break;
    case 'loading':
      // no extra properties
      break;
  }
}

Perfect for: API states, form states, event handling, Redux actions.

Mapped types transform every property of a type:

type Readonly<T> = {
  readonly [K in keyof T]: T[K];
};

type Optional<T> = {
  [K in keyof T]?: T[K];
};

type Nullable<T> = {
  [K in keyof T]: T[K] | null;
};

With key remapping (as):
type Getters<T> = {
  [K in keyof T as `get${Capitalize<string & K>}`]: () => T[K];
};
// { getName: () => string; getAge: () => number; }

Mapped types power most built-in utility types (Partial, Required, Readonly, Record).

'as const' makes values deeply readonly and narrows their types to literal types:

const colors = ['red', 'blue'] as const;
// type: readonly ['red', 'blue'] (not string[])

const config = {
  api: 'https://api.example.com',
  timeout: 3000,
} as const;
// type: { readonly api: 'https://...'; readonly timeout: 3000 }

Use cases:
• Enum-like constant objects
• Route definitions
• Action type strings (Redux)
• Function arguments that should be literal types
• Config objects

Combines well with typeof: type Color = typeof colors[number]; // 'red' | 'blue'

Types that choose between two types based on a condition:

type IsString<T> = T extends string ? 'yes' : 'no';

IsString<string>  // 'yes'
IsString<number>  // 'no'

With infer (extract types):
type ReturnType<T> = T extends (...args: any[]) => infer R ? R : never;
type Unwrap<T> = T extends Promise<infer U> ? U : T;

Unwrap<Promise<string>> // string
Unwrap<number>          // number

Conditional types + infer are how most advanced utility types work. They're like pattern matching for types.

satisfies validates that a value matches a type WITHOUT widening it:

type Colors = Record<string, string | string[]>;

const palette = {
  red: '#ff0000',
  blue: ['#0000ff', '#0000cc'],
} satisfies Colors;

palette.red.toUpperCase();  // ✅ TS knows it's string
palette.blue.map(c => c);   // ✅ TS knows it's string[]

Without satisfies (using : Colors):
palette.red.toUpperCase();  // ❌ Error: could be string | string[]

satisfies = type-check + keep narrow type. Best of both worlds.

Types built from string template syntax:

type EventName = `on${Capitalize<string>}`;
// matches: 'onClick', 'onHover', 'onAnything'

type CSSProperty = `${string}-${string}`;
// matches: 'font-size', 'background-color'

Practical example:
type Routes = '/users' | '/posts';
type ApiEndpoint = `GET ${Routes}` | `POST ${Routes}`;
// 'GET /users' | 'GET /posts' | 'POST /users' | 'POST /posts'

Used heavily in: type-safe event systems, CSS-in-JS, API route typing, i18n keys.

Common patterns:

// Basic props
interface ButtonProps {
  label: string;
  onClick: () => void;
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary';
}

// Extending HTML elements
interface ButtonProps extends React.ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement> {
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary';
}

// Children
interface LayoutProps {
  children: React.ReactNode;
}

// Generic components
interface ListProps<T> {
  items: T[];
  renderItem: (item: T) => React.ReactNode;
}

// Discriminated union props
type ModalProps =
  | { mode: 'create'; onSubmit: (data: FormData) => void }
  | { mode: 'view'; data: Item }

never represents values that never occur:

// Function that never returns
function throwError(msg: string): never {
  throw new Error(msg);
}

// Exhaustiveness checking (most useful!):
type Shape = 'circle' | 'square';
function area(shape: Shape) {
  switch (shape) {
    case 'circle': return Math.PI;
    case 'square': return 1;
    default:
      const _exhaustive: never = shape;
      // If you add 'triangle' to Shape but forget a case,
      // TypeScript errors HERE at compile time!
      return _exhaustive;
  }
}

never = type system's way of saying 'this is impossible'.

When two declarations with the same name exist, TypeScript merges them:

interface User { name: string; }
interface User { age: number; }
// Result: interface User { name: string; age: number; }

Useful for:
• Extending third-party types without modifying source
• Adding properties to Window, Process, etc.

declare global {
  interface Window {
    myApp: { version: string };
  }
}

• Module augmentation:
declare module 'express' {
  interface Request {
    user?: User;
  }
}

Note: 'type' aliases do NOT merge — only interfaces do.
